  <h2>The Brief</h2>
  <p>
    Queensland Government facilities span a wide range of building types and security classifications — courts, government service centres, correctional facilities, departmental offices, regional service buildings and remote community infrastructure. Cleaning these environments is not a discretionary maintenance function. It is a compliance obligation under the Queensland Government's procurement framework, with documented performance obligations, security access requirements, incident reporting standards and audit processes that operate continuously through the life of the contract.
  </p>
  <p>
    The QBuild panel framework exists precisely because government cleaning is different from commercial cleaning — it requires providers who meet pre-qualification standards across safety, compliance, financial capacity and management systems before they can tender. It requires ongoing compliance, not just demonstrated capability at point of tender.
  </p>

  <h2>The Approach</h2>
  <p>
    CPC's approach to Queensland Government cleaning is built on three pillars: certified management systems, compliance-controlled workforce management, and reporting infrastructure that meets government accountability requirements.
  </p>
  <p>
    The certified management systems — ISO 9001 for quality, ISO 14001 for environmental management, ISO 45001 for work health and safety — provide the documented framework under which every site is managed. These are not marketing credentials; they are operational systems with internal audit requirements, nonconformance processes and management review cycles that apply to every site in the portfolio. When a government client requests evidence of management system compliance, the documentation exists because the system operates, not because it was assembled for the request.
  </p>
  <p>
    Workforce management under Queensland Government contracts requires that all personnel deployed to sensitive sites meet the security screening requirements of that site's classification. CPC's compliance-controlled workforce model maintains credential records, manages renewal cycles and ensures that access is only granted to personnel whose credentials are current. This is not a manual process — it is managed through documented credential management protocols that operate continuously.
  </p>

  <h2>The Operation</h2>
  <p>
    CPC has operated under the QBuild Panel since 1997. The current portfolio spans 252 sites across Queensland — metropolitan sites in Brisbane and Southeast Queensland, regional sites across the state, and remote sites in areas where logistics and workforce management present challenges that metropolitan-only providers cannot reliably address.
  </p>
  <p>
    The geographic spread of the Queensland Government portfolio is the most demanding test of operational scale. A provider capable of managing a metro portfolio of a few dozen sites is not automatically capable of managing sites in regional and remote Queensland where workforce sourcing, materials logistics and emergency response require different operational infrastructure. CPC's 28-year operating history in this portfolio demonstrates that the remote and regional capability is real, not aspirational.
  </p>
  <p>
    The portfolio includes facilities with varying access conditions, security classifications and operational schedules. Government service centres require cleaning around public access hours. Courts and justice facilities require access management and security coordination. Regional and remote facilities require self-sufficient operational capability. Each site type has its own compliance requirements; the management system must accommodate all of them simultaneously.
  </p>

  <h2>Compliance and Standards</h2>
  <p>
    The compliance framework for the Queensland Government portfolio operates across four dimensions:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ISO 9001:2015</strong>. Quality Management System certification, requiring documented processes, measurable quality objectives, internal audit and management review across all service delivery.</li>
    <li><strong>ISO 14001:2015</strong>. Environmental Management System certification, requiring environmental impact assessment, chemical management protocols and waste minimisation documentation.</li>
    <li><strong>ISO 45001:2018</strong>. Occupational Health and Safety Management System certification, requiring hazard identification, risk control, incident investigation and safety performance measurement for every site type in the portfolio.</li>
    <li><strong>QBuild Panel conditions</strong>. Queensland Government procurement requirements including modern slavery compliance, insurance coverage, workforce credentials, performance reporting and contract management obligations that operate continuously through the contract term.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Security screening requirements are managed at the site level — each facility's security classification determines the screening requirements for personnel accessing that site. CPC's credential management system maintains the records necessary to demonstrate compliance at any individual site in the portfolio on demand.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    28 years of continuous service under the QBuild Panel is the primary outcome evidence. Panel frameworks are designed to remove non-performing providers — continuation is not automatic. The sustained position across three decades of Queensland Government procurement reflects performance outcomes across successive contract periods, panel renewals and operational requirement changes.
  </p>
  <p>
    The 252-site scale demonstrates that the management infrastructure required to support a large government portfolio — compliance documentation, credential management, performance reporting, incident response, audit preparation — is operational, not theoretical. Any site in the portfolio can be audited at any time; the documentation and evidence trail exist because the management system operates continuously, not because audits prompt assembly of evidence.
  </p>
  <p>
    The geographic range — metro, regional and remote — demonstrates operational capability that panel evaluators weight heavily in procurement decisions. Providers who cannot credibly demonstrate remote and regional delivery capability are effectively limited to metropolitan contracts regardless of their management system certifications.
  </p>

